Headlines.Author: Drew FitzGerald
Headlines.Headline: DealerTrak To Buy Auto Data Firm TriVIN For $131M

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES DealerTrack Holdings Inc. TRAK agreed to buy auto title management company triVIN Holdings Inc. for $131 million in cash as the software maker looks to expand its offerings to lenders and auto dealers. DealerTrack, which makes software for auto dealers, swung to a profit in the third quarter. DealerTrack, which expects the deal to close in the first quarter, operates the industry's largest online credit application network, which connects auto dealers with lenders. TriVIN's FDI Collateral Management business provides lien and title information that allows lenders to outsource the management of vehicles and titles held as collateral.

Headlines.Author: John Spence
Headlines.Headline: Amer Capital Raised To Outperform From Underperform By BMO Capital

PARAGRAPH.#text: BMO Capital Markets analyst David Chiaverini on Wednesday upgraded American Capital Ltd. (ACAS)  to outperform from underperform "owing to an improvement in balance sheet strength, our belief that the company will come to a satisfactory agreement with lenders, and an improved outlook for its owned equity investments." He also pointed to the company last week receiving a $295 million equity infusion from investors including hedge-fund manager Paulson & Co., which acquired a 13% stake. In a research note, David Chiaverini said he has attributed a speculative rating to his outperform on the stock as the company remains in default on $2.4 billion of unsecured debt. "The equity infusion helps provide us with a visible pathway of American Capital getting out of default and returning to normal business conditions, but there can be no assurance that this will pan out as we expect." American Capital shares were up nearly 5% in recent premarket trading Wednesday.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Amer Capital Raised To Outperform From Underperform By BMO Capital

Headlines.Author: Josh Beckerman
Headlines.Headline: $37M Doesn't Seem Like Much Now

PARAGRAPH.#text: There are many classic ratios out there - P/E, debt-to-Ebitda - but new times demand new metrics. How about the exit proceeds-to-stock increase ratio?When American Capital Ltd. announced a $16 million gain on an exit of an undisclosed portfolio company, its stock closed up 15.8% to $2.64. Total proceeds on that deal were $37 million; the 39% compounded IRR was impressive but it didn't seem like a mega-deal for a firm of American Capital's size.So, today, when Corning Inc. announced that it bought American Capital-owned Axygen BioScience Inc. for $400 million, we thought that would likely help the business development company's stock price. This was by far the firm's biggest exit this year and nine-figure deals are rare all around.UPDATE: We've included returns information on Axygen from American Capital's recently issued press release.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: $37M Doesn't Seem Like Much Now

Headlines.Author: Paul Hodkinson
Headlines.Headline: Financial News: 3i, American Capital To Make Job Cuts

PARAGRAPH.#text: Buyout firms 3i (III.LN) and American Capital are set to be the latest private equity operations to cut staff as the economic downturn begins to hit the industry directly. U.K.-listed 3i is expected to announce Thursday that it will slash about 100, or 15%, of its estimated 660 staff. Between March and September, the firm had an average of 739 staff, which dropped after it closed its Menlo Park venture capital operation in California. Headlines.Author: Brian Kalish
Headlines.Headline: SEC Charges Beverly Hills Firm With Illegal Short Selling

PARAGRAPH.#text: The Securities and Exchange Commission said on Tuesday it has charged a Beverly Hills firm and its principal with illegal short-selling in 14 publicly traded companies. Lions Gate Capital Inc. and its principal, Kenneth Rickel, are alleged to have used shares purchased in public offerings to cover short sales that occurred during the five business days before the pricing of the offerings, according to an SEC press release. The SEC alleges that Rickel made at least $207,291 in profits from illegal trades.
